California groundwater levels in the past 10 years: a case study

Kinga Bihari

2024-06-02

In this project, I’m looking at historical groundwater level and dry well data in California in order to quantify how groundwater levels have changed in the past 10 years.

One dataset is the amount of dry wells that have been reported (including lat/long, county, well depth and date reported) between 2005-2023.

Another dataset is daily groundwater levels (including county and lat/long) for the same time period.

Sources:
United States Geological Survey (groundwater levels)
California Open Data Portal (dry wells)
California Open Data Portal (CA state boundary)

Research questions:
Plot 1: How have groundwater levels in San Bernardino County changed between 2013-2023, and how many wells have been reported dry in the same time period?
Plot 2: How do the number of reported dry wells between 2013-2023 vary across counties in California?

Conclusions:
Plot 1: Show how groundwater levels have changed from 2013-2023 in San Bernardino County, and how they compare to the number of wells that have gone dry during the same time period.
Plot 2: Show how the amount of wells that have gone dry differ from county to county based on where they’re located.

# new san bernardino county dataframe for plotting (also combine 5 parts into one)
san_bernardino1_plot <- san_bernardino1 |>                                      # call original dataframe   
                        rename("level_max" = "x230641_62611_00001",
                               "date" = datetime,
                               "site" = site_no) |>                             # rename columns for easier reading
                        select(date, site, level_max)                           # select relevant columns
san_bernardino2_plot <- san_bernardino2 |>                                      # call original dataframe   
                        rename("level_max" = "x230641_62611_00001",
                               "date" = datetime,

                        select(date, site, level_max)                           # select relevant columns
san_bernardino3_plot <- san_bernardino3 |>                                      # call original dataframe   
                        rename("level_max" = "x230641_62611_00001",
                               "date" = datetime,

san_bernardino5_plot <- san_bernardino5 |>                                      # call original dataframe   
                        rename("level_max" = "x230641_62611_00001",
                               "date" = datetime,
                               "site" = site_no) |>                             # rename columns for easier reading
                        select(date, site, level_max)                           # select relevant columns
# combine parts & continue organization
sb_levels <- rbind(san_bernardino1_plot, 
                   san_bernardino2_plot, 
                   san_bernardino3_plot, 
                   san_bernardino4_plot, 
                   san_bernardino5_plot) |>                                     # use rbind to combine into one dataframe
                   mutate("level" = level_max) |>                               # simplify "level" column name 
                   select(date, site, level) |>                                 # select relevant columns
                   na.omit() |>                                                 # remove rows (dates) with no data 
                   arrange(desc(date)) |>                                       # reorder by date 
                   slice(32317:386043)                                          # choose dates 2013-01-01 to 2023-01-01 (for exaclty 10 years of data)

# supplementary dataframe to help find best representative monitoring sites by ones with the most data 
sb_sum <- sb_levels |>                                                          # call original dataframe
          mutate(occurence = 1) |>                                              # add column "occurence" to be able to sum # of datapoints for each site
          group_by(site) |>                                                     # group by site
          summarize_at("occurence", sum) |>                                     # sum occurences by site
          ungroup() |>                                                          # ungroup!
          arrange(-occurence) |>                                                # order from high to low
          slice(1:10)                                                           # choose top 10 sites with most data

# list of top 10 monitoring sites (aka very basic data dictionary)

#340615117170902 = site4

site2 <- sb_levels |>                                                           # same as above
         filter(site %in% "340046117020803")
site3 <- sb_levels |> 
         filter(site %in% "340503117104101")
site4 <- sb_levels |> 
         filter(site %in% "340615117170902")

site6 <- sb_levels |>

         filter(site %in% "340521117212005")
site8 <- sb_levels |> 
         filter(site %in% "340927117242201")

# exploratory plot of monitoring wells in San Bernardino county to see which sites I should use as representative for the whole county          
ggplot() +                                                                      # plot all on same graph to see trends
  geom_line(data = site1, aes(x = date, y = level)) +                           # identify dataframe & x/y axes
  geom_line(data = site2, aes(x = date, y = level)) +                           # same as above
  geom_line(data = site3, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site4, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site5, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site6, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site7, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site8, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site9, aes(x = date, y = level)) +
  geom_line(data = site10, aes(x = date, y = level))

# based on exploratory plot, will use sites 1, 4, 7 & 10
# create dataframe with only relevant sites for plotting
well_sites <- rbind(site1, site4, site7, site10) |>                             # call 4 sites w most data & combine
              pivot_wider(names_from = "site", values_from = "level") |>        # pivot wider so eac site is its own column
              rename("site1" = "340521117212001", 
                     "site4" = "340615117170902",
                     "site7" = "340521117212005",
                     "site10" = "340508117163303") |>                           # rename sites w/ better names
              pivot_longer(2:5, names_to = "site", values_to = "level")         # pivot back to original form for plotting

# 2nd dataset: create new object from original dataframe for plotting 

# new reported dry wells dataframe with just wells from San Bernardino county
sb_wells <- dry_wells |>                                                        # call original dataframe
            filter(county %in% "San Bernardino") |>                             # only select wells in San Bernardino
            arrange(report_date) |>                                             # reorder by report date 
            select(report_date, latitude, longitude, city, id) |>               # select relevant columns
            na.omit() |>                                                        # remove rows w no data
            mutate(occurence = c(0, 10, 20, 
                                 0, 10, 
                                 0, 10, 20, 30, 40,
                                 0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 
                                 0, 10, 
                                 0))                                            # add occurence column for plotting

Step 4: Plot 1

# create coefficient for transforming second axis
coeff <- 735

# figure 1: 4 representative monitoring wells' water levels between 2013-2023 for San Bernardino county + number of wells that have gone dry in the same time period and county
ggplot() +
  
# 1st geom: line graphs showing water levels for 4 monitoring wells (in feet above NAVD 1988)
  geom_line(data = well_sites,                                                  # identify dataframe
            aes(x = date, y = level,                                            # identify x/y axes
                group = site, color = site),                                    # identify how to group/color lines
            size = 1.5) +                                                       # line size
           
# 2nd geom: point plot showing number of wells that have gone dry 
  geom_point(data = sb_wells,                                                   # identify dataframe               
           aes(x = report_date, y = occurence + coeff),                         # x/y axes & transformation for 2nd axis
           size = 8.5, color = "#4292c6") +                                     # size/color
  
# labels 
  labs(x = "Year", 
       y = "Groundwater level above NAVD 1988 (feet)",                          # x/y axis labels 
       caption = "Figure 1: Groundwater levels and reported dry wells in San Bernardino County, CA from 2013-2023. 
       Data from USGS and California Open Data Portal.") +                      # caption

# axis formatting 
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 year",                                          # group dates by year
               date_labels = "%Y",                                              # identify how dates shown on axis
               expand = c(0, 0)) +                                              # no gaps between data/axis
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0),                                          # no gaps between data/axis
                     limits = c(730, 930),                                      # y axis limits
                     breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10),                    # axis label breaks
                     sec.axis = sec_axis(trans = ~.*0.1-73,                     # add 2nd axis & using transformation
                                name = "Reported dry wells (# of wells)",       # label axis 
                                breaks = 1:20)) +                               # axis labels -> start w/ 1 instead of 0    
  
# coloring for 1st geom
  scale_color_manual(values = c(site1 = "#c2a5cf",
                                site4 = "#66c2a5",
                                site7 = "#fc8d62",
                                site10 = "#e78ac3"),                             # assign colors to the sites
                     labels = c(site1 = "Site 1",
                                site7 = "Site 4",
                                site4 = "Site 3", 
                                site10 = "Site 2"),                             # assign legend names to the column names
                     name = "Monitoring Well Sites") +                          # name legend
  
# theme stuff: aesthetics
  ggplot2::theme_linedraw() +                                                   # plain background w/ major gridlines
  theme(axis.text = element_text(color = "#000000", size = 12),                 # axis numbers color/size
        axis.text.y.right = element_text(color = "#4292c6", size = 10),         # 2nd y axis color to match data color
        axis.text.y.left = element_text(color = "#000000", size = 10),          # 1st y axis color/size
        axis.title.x = element_text(color = "#000000", size = 15,               # x axis label color/size
                                    face = "bold",                              # bold text
                                    margin = margin(t = 5, "mm")),              # margin around axis
        axis.title.y.left = element_text(color = "#000000", size = 15,          # y axis label color/size
                                         face = "bold",                         # bold text
                                         margin = margin(r = 8, "mm")),         # margin around axis
        axis.title.y.right = element_text(color = "#4292c6", size = 15,         # 2nd y axis label color/size (matches data color)
                                          face = "bold",                        # bold text
                                          margin = margin(l = 10, "mm")),       # adjust margin between axis title & text     
        plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.5, color = "#000000",             # align caption, color
                                    size = 16, face = "bold"),                  # caption size/bold 
        legend.text = element_text(size = 14),                                  # legend text size
        legend.title = element_text(color = "#000000", size = 14, 
                                    face = "bold"),                             # legend title size/color/bold
        legend.position = "top",                                                # legend position
        legend.margin = margin(0, 0, 0, 0),                                     # no margin around legend
        plot.margin = margin(1, 5, 5, 1, "mm"))                                 # margins around graph (so x axis text isn't cut off)

Plot 1 conclusion:
Groundwater levels in San Bernardino have been steadily decreasing over the past decade, based on 4 representative wells. Reported dry wells have also increased as the decade has progressed.

Step 5: Organize data for Plot 2

# 3rd dataset: create new object from original dataframe for mapping

# new county boundaries data frame for joining with dry wells occurences
counties_plot <- counties |>                                                    # call dataframe
                 st_transform(5070) |>                                          # identify projection
                 select(countyfp, "county" = name)                              # select relevant columns

# 2nd dataset: create new objects from original dataframes for plotting

# new reported dry wells dataframe for plotting
wells_plot <- dry_wells |>                                                      # call original dataframe
              mutate(occurence = 1)                                             # add column "occurence" to be able to sum how many wells were reported dry by county (see county_map)

# supplementary dataframe to get number of dry wells per county for 2nd plot 
county_map <- wells_plot |>                                                     # call original dataframe
              select(county, occurence) |>                                      # select relevant columns
              group_by(county) |>                                               # group by county
              summarize_at(1, sum, na.rm = TRUE) |>                             # sum occurences by county
              ungroup() |>                                                      # ungroup!
              right_join(counties_plot, by = "county") |>                       # join spatial info to wells info
              mutate_at(vars(2), ~replace(., is.na(.), 0)) |>                   # replace NA values w/ 0 so all counties will have a value
              st_as_sf(crs = 5070)                                              # make dataframe an sf

Step 6: Plot 2

# figure 2: geospatial map of the number of wells that have gone dry by county in CA
ggplot(data = county_map) +                                                     # identify dataframe

# 1st geom: geospatial map showing # of reported wells per county
  geom_sf(mapping = aes(fill = occurence),                                      # fill counties by # of reported dry wells
          col = "white", size = 10) +                                           # county boundary line color/size
  
# labels
  labs(x = " ", y = " ",                                                        # no x/y labels for clean look
  caption = "Figure 2: Reported dry wells by county in California between 2013-2023. 
       Data from California Open Data Portal.") +                               # caption

# 2nd geom: label county names 
  geom_sf_text(aes(label = county),                                             # label county names
               size = 1.5, color = "#000000") +                                 # color/size 
  
# color in counties
  scale_fill_gradient(name = "Reported Dry Wells",                              # name legend
                      trans = "log2",                                           # transform legend to be logrithmic to fit data
                      breaks = c(0, 1, 10, 100, 1000),                          # identify breaks on legend              
                      labels = scales::comma,                                   # add commas
                               c(0, 1, 10, 100, 1000),                          # identify break labels
                      low = "#c6dbef", high = "#225ea8",                        # identify color scale
                      na.value = "#e0f3f8") +                                   # identify color for 0 wells reported
                      
# theme stuff: aesthetics
  theme_light() +                                                               # plain background w/ box around map
  theme(legend.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold"),                  # legend text size/bold                                 
        legend.position = c(.95, 0.8),                                          # put legend inside plot
        legend.justification = c("right", "top"),                               # legend location
        legend.box.just = "right",                                              # legend justification
        legend.margin = margin(4, 4, 4, 4),                                     # margin around legend
        legend.key = element_rect(colour = "#000000"),                          # format color scale
        plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.5,                                # caption justification
                                    color = "#000000", size = 12,               # caption color
                                    face = "bold",                              # bold
                                    margin = margin(t = 0, "mm")),              # margin around caption
        panel.grid = element_blank(),                                           # no gridlines
        axis.text = element_text(color = "#000000", size = 7))                  # axis text color & size

Figure 2: Reported dry wells by county in California between 2013-2023. Data from California Open Data Portal.

Plot 2 conclusion:
The number of reported dry wells over the past decade have been overwhelmingly from agricultural areas, like the central valley. This is because agriculture relies heavily on wells for irrigation & water is getting scarcer.
